      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "FAQPage",
          "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage",
          "name": "Answers to auto financing questions",
          "mainEntity": [
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_0_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question",
              "name": "How much experience does Wells Fargo have with auto financing?",
              "acceptedAnswer": [
                {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_0_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question_acceptedAnswer_Answer",
                  "text": "Wells Fargo has more than 50 years of experience in new and used car financing. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_1_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question",
              "name": "How do I apply for a Wells Fargo auto loan?",
              "acceptedAnswer": [
                {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_1_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question_acceptedAnswer_Answer",
                  "text": "Wells Fargo auto loans are only available through our nationwide network of nearly 11,000 dealerships. Be sure to ask your dealership if Wells Fargo auto financing is available. If your loan is funded by Wells Fargo Auto, we'll service your account. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_2_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question",
              "name": "What are aftermarket products?",
              "acceptedAnswer": [
                {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_2_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question_acceptedAnswer_Answer",
                  "text": "Aftermarket products are optional products or services that may be purchased from the dealership along with your vehicle. Some examples include:  Guaranteed Asset Protection (GAP) covers all or a portion of the loan balance after the payment of a total loss insurance claim. Service contracts (also referred to as extended warranties) provide coverage in the event that a major mechanical component of the vehicle, such as an engine, transmission, heating/cooling system, seal, gasket, and/or fuel system, needs repair. The coverage typically lasts for a specific period of time or vehicle mileage. Anti-theft protection includes devices or services, such as tracking, that make the vehicle (or the component of the vehicle) more difficult to steal or easier to recover if it’s stolen. It can also provide a financial benefit after a theft. Surface protection for the interior or exterior of the vehicle. Maintenance packages are prepaid plans that typically cover scheduled maintenance, such as oil changes, on the vehicle.  "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_3_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question",
              "name": "What is Guaranteed Asset Protection (GAP)?",
              "acceptedAnswer": [
                {
                  "@type": "Answer",
                  "@id": "https://www.wellsfargo.com/auto-loans/vehicle-financing-101/#Highlight20251015194248163-32952_3_AboutPage_mainEntity_FAQPage_mainEntity_Question_acceptedAnswer_Answer",
                  "text": "GAP is an optional product that covers any \"gap\" between the amount owed on the loan and the vehicle's value in the event of a total loss. Some exclusions apply. It's important to review the coverage details to understand the limitations of GAP coverage. Example  Your vehicle was in an accident and deemed a total loss. Your insurance company determines that the fair market value of the vehicle at the time of the loss is $10,000, so that's what they paid out. The remaining loan balance on the vehicle is $13,000. After insurance, you still owe $3,000. If you have GAP, the remaining $3,000 may be covered. GAP may not cover late payments, late fees, or deferred payments. "
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
      "name": "A guide to new and used car loans | Wells Fargo"
    }
